      <hedline>
        <hl1>Cuban History Question</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Theodore S Corin letter says Cuban exiles should consider to what extent Fulgencio Batista's corrupt right-wing despotism unwittingly spawned Fidel Castro's reactive left-wing tyranny (May 13 Arts &amp; Ideas section)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Amid a Thaw, Cuba Studies Get Hot'' (Arts &amp; Ideas pages, May 13):</p>
        <p>Although it might upset anti-Castro exiles, a balanced scholarly dissertation on the 1959 Cuban revolution could help answer this question: To what extent, if any, did Fulgencio Batista's corrupt right-wing despotism unwittingly spawn Fidel Castro's reactive left-wing tyranny?</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Amid a Thaw, Cuba Studies Get Hot'' (Arts &amp; Ideas pages, May 13):</p>
        <p>Although it might upset anti-Castro exiles, a balanced scholarly dissertation on the 1959 Cuban revolution could help answer this question: To what extent, if any, did Fulgencio Batista's corrupt right-wing despotism unwittingly spawn Fidel Castro's reactive left-wing tyranny?</p>
        <p>A little more history and a lot less emotion would serve us well.</p>
        <p>THEODORE S. CORIN  Austin, Tex., May 15, 2000</p>
      </block>
